#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_storage.xml:9
#, no-c-format
msgid "Managing Storage"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:15
#, no-c-format
msgid "When managing a &vmguest; on the &vmhost; itself, you can access the complete file system of the &vmhost; to attach or create virtual hard disks or to attach existing images to the &vmguest;. However, this is not possible when managing &vmguest;s from a remote host. For this reason, &libvirt; supports so called <quote>Storage Pools</quote> , which can be accessed from remote machines."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_storage.xml:24
#, no-c-format
msgid "CD/DVD ISO images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:25
#, no-c-format
msgid "To be able to access CD/DVD ISO images on the &vmhost; from remote, they also need to be placed in a storage pool."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:30
#, no-c-format
msgid "&libvirt; knows two different types of storage: volumes and pools."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:35
#, no-c-format
msgid "Storage Volume"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:37
#, no-c-format
msgid "A storage volume is a storage device that can be assigned to a guest&mdash;a virtual disk or a CD/DVD/floppy image. Physically (on the &vmhost;) it can be a block device (a partition, a logical volume, etc.) or a file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:46
#, no-c-format
msgid "Storage Pool"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:48
#, no-c-format
msgid "A storage pool is a storage resource on the &vmhost; that can be used for storing volumes, similar to network storage for a desktop machine. Physically it can be one of the following types:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:55
#, no-c-format
msgid "File System Directory ( <guimenu>dir</guimenu> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:57
#, no-c-format
msgid "A directory for hosting image files. The files can be either one of the supported disk formats (raw, qcow2, or qed), or ISO images."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:64
#, no-c-format
msgid "Physical Disk Device ( <guimenu>disk</guimenu> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:66
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use a complete physical disk as storage. A partition is created for each volume that is added to the pool."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:73
#, no-c-format
msgid "Pre-Formatted Block Device ( <guimenu>fs</guimenu> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:75
#, no-c-format
msgid "Specify a partition to be used in the same way as a file system directory pool (a directory for hosting image files). The only difference to using a file system directory is that &libvirt; takes care of mounting the device."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:92
#, no-c-format
msgid "iSCSI Target (iscsi)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:94
#, no-c-format
msgid "Set up a pool on an iSCSI target. You need to have been logged in to the volume once before, to use it with &libvirt;. Use the &yast; <guimenu>iSCSI Initiator</guimenu> to detect and log in to a volume <phrase os=\"sles\">, see <xref linkend=\"book.storage\"/> for details</phrase> . Volume creation on iSCSI pools is not supported, instead each existing Logical Unit Number (LUN) represents a volume. Each volume/LUN also needs a valid (empty) partition table or disk label before you can use it. If missing, use <command>fdisk</command> to add it:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_storage.xml:105
#, no-c-format
msgid "~ # fdisk -cu /dev/disk/by-path/ip-&wsIip;:3260-iscsi-iqn.2010-10.com.example:[...]-lun-2\n"
      "Device contains neither a valid DOS partition table, nor Sun, SGI\n"
      "or OSF disklabel\n"
      "Building a new DOS disklabel with disk identifier 0xc15cdc4e.\n"
      "Changes will remain in memory only, until you decide to write them.\n"
      "After that, of course, the previous content won't be recoverable.\n"
      "\n"
      "Warning: invalid flag 0x0000 of partition table 4 will be corrected by w(rite)\n"
      "\n"
      "Command (m for help): w\n"
      "The partition table has been altered!\n"
      "\n"
      "Calling ioctl() to re-read partition table.\n"
      "Syncing disks."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:122
#, no-c-format
msgid "LVM Volume Group (logical)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:124
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use an LVM volume group as a pool. You may either use a predefined volume group, or create a group by specifying the devices to use. Storage volumes are created as partitions on the volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_storage.xml:130
#, no-c-format
msgid "Deleting the LVM-Based Pool"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:131
#, no-c-format
msgid "When the LVM-based pool is deleted in the Storage Manager, the volume group is deleted as well. This results in a non-recoverable loss of all data stored on the pool!"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:140
#, no-c-format
msgid "Multipath Devices ( <guimenu>mpath</guimenu> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:142
#, no-c-format
msgid "At the moment, multipathing support is limited to assigning existing devices to the guests. Volume creation or configuring multipathing from within &libvirt; is not supported."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:150
#, no-c-format
msgid "Network Exported Directory ( <guimenu>netfs</guimenu> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:152
#, no-c-format
msgid "Specify a network directory to be used in the same way as a file system directory pool (a directory for hosting image files). The only difference to using a file system directory is that &libvirt; takes care of mounting the directory. Supported protocols are NFS and GlusterFS."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_storage.xml:178
#, no-c-format
msgid "SCSI Host Adapter ( <guimenu>scsi</guimenu> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:180
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use an SCSI host adapter in almost the same way as an iSCSI target. We recommend to use a device name from <filename>/dev/disk/by-*</filename> rather than <filename>/dev/sd<replaceable>X</replaceable></filename> . The latter can change (for example, when adding or removing hard disks). Volume creation on iSCSI pools is not supported. Instead, each existing LUN (Logical Unit Number) represents a volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_storage.xml:196
#, no-c-format
msgid "Security Considerations"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:197
#, no-c-format
msgid "To avoid data loss or data corruption, do not attempt to use resources such as LVM volume groups, iSCSI targets, etc., that are also used to build storage pools on the &vmhost;. There is no need to connect to these resources from the &vmhost; or to mount them on the &vmhost;&mdash;&libvirt; takes care of this."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:204
#, no-c-format
msgid "Do not mount partitions on the &vmhost; by label. Under certain circumstances it is possible that a partition is labeled from within a &vmguest; with a name already existing on the &vmhost;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_storage.xml:211
#, no-c-format
msgid "Managing Storage with &vmm;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_storage.xml:213
#, no-c-format
msgid "The &vmm; provides a graphical interface&mdash;the Storage Manager&mdash;to manage storage volumes and pools. To access it, either right-click a connection and choose <guimenu>Details</guimenu> , or highlight a connection and choose <menuchoice> <guimenu>Edit</guimenu> <guimenu>Connection Details</guimenu> </menuchoice> . Select the <guimenu>Storage</guimenu> tab."
msgstr ""

